node.text:
“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

It is the way we break free from antiquated norms in all capacities and how we emerge into a world that is truly equal for all. Being #queer doesn’t mean you all of a sudden sleep with someone only the same sex. It means your open your mind up to a new way of living that isn’t rooted in the pain of the patriarchy and religion. Happy #Pride Month y’all.” (Posted with consent) #pride2021 #lesbian #gay #bisexual #transgender #intersex #asexual #demisexual #pansexual

node.text:
Our art curator @amandabjorn interviewed @lydiametral for this week’s #feministartfeature series. She is one of our winners for the Pride Photo Contest! Lydia is a French self-taught photographer with a Spanish background working between Paris and Barcelona. Les Insouciants (The Reckless) is a documentary project about young adults who feel different, who don’t fit in the standards of society, and who try to escape the established norms. For five years, Lydia has been taking photos of friends, acquaintances and people she met through the project itself within the queer community with the intention to give them visibility, to show them as they really are in a space forged in their image, and where they can express themselves freely. 

Can you share something you've learned from creating this body of work that would resonate with our community? As a queer woman, I was really interested in immersing myself in the queer community. When I was younger I wish I had experienced more queer imagery, that would have helped me to understand and accept myself a lot more. In this project I am interested in taking portraits in intimate spaces, forged in my model's image. I want to show them as they really are, with no artifice, mostly at home or in spaces where they would feel safe and identify with their surroundings. 

To read more and see the winning photo series for our Pride Photo Contest, check out the link in our bio!
